Something higher up can catch, if need be. this way you can write a function which is supposed to throw exceptions in cases of failure, but not leave resources hanging about. An example would be executing arbitrary SQL; you might want to do;<p><pre><code>  01 void ExecuteSql(string sql)
  02 {
  03   connection.Open();
  04   try
  05   {
  06     // execute SQL
  07   }
  08   finally
  09   {
  10     connection.Close();
  11   }
  12 }
</code></pre>
And the effect here is that you have a function which still throws if your SQL is bad, but doesn't have the side-effect of leaving you with an open connection dangling about. That feels like a safer function to call.<p>try/finally isn't something I find myself using very often at all, I think because the IDisposable pattern is actually translated into it - the code above is (nearly?) equivalent to;<p><pre><code>  connection.Open();
  using(connection)
  {
    // execute SQL
  }
</code></pre>
so I guess IDisposable is the preferred way in MS' codebase.<p>(All code is typed late at night into a textbox and totally untested. ;) )<p>PS: @politician confirms that `using` is translated to try/finally (<a href="http://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=3440969" rel="nofollow">http://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=3440969</a>) so that's why you don't see it much -- `using` is syntactic sugar for it.
